{"headline_summary": "The Provider Manual, with an effective date of October 1, 2025, is significantly more recent than the newest relevant Policy document (July 1, 2020, for billing responsibility, or October 1, 2022, for general pharmacy billing reminders) and should receive more weight for current guidance. According to the Provider Manual, home infusion drugs are covered as a pharmacy or medical benefit, not a bundled payment, and the provider/pharmacy is responsible for determining other insurance coverage and billing the appropriate party, including third-party insurers first.", "policy_definition": "Insufficient grounded evidence in the provided documents to define how home infusion drugs are specifically covered for Policy. The policy documents discuss payment for drug administration in clinic/inpatient settings [New York State Medicaid Update November 2019 Volume 35 Number 11:5 — 2019-11-01] and general pharmacy billing reminders [New York State Medicaid Update October 2022 Volume 38 Number 12:7 — 2022-10-01], but do not define the coverage mechanism for home infusion drugs themselves.

Regarding billing responsibility, it is the "pharmacy’s responsibility to bill timely and to the appropriate party, i.e., the facility, commercial plan, Medicare, or Medicaid" [New York State Medicaid Update July 2020 Volume 36 Number 12:8 — 2020-07-01]. Providers, including pharmacies, are responsible for actively and regularly seeking Third Party Liability (TPL) enrollment and Medicaid eligibility for their patients [New York State Medicaid Update July 2020 Volume 36 Number 12:8 — 2020-07-01]. New York State Medicaid is always the payor of last resort, requiring providers to obtain correct billing information, bill third-party insurers first (including commercial plans or Medicare), and resolve any claim issues, such as prior authorization, prior to submitting the claim to Medicaid as secondary [New York State Medicaid Update June 2019 Volume 35 Number 7:5 — 2019-06-01].", "provider_manual_definition": "The New York State Medicaid Program "does not provide a bundled payment to cover drugs, supplies and services associated with home infusion treatments" [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Policy Guidelines:19 — 2025-10-01]. Instead, "Home infusion drugs and supplies must be billed as a pharmacy or medical benefit" [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Policy Guidelines:19 — 2025-10-01]. NYS Medicaid recognizes the need for "certain drugs, including home infusion drugs, requiring administration by a health care provider to be available to members by way of both the medical benefit and pharmacy benefit" [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Policy Guidelines:12 — 2025-10-01]. Drugs are evaluated for pharmacy benefit coverage based on criteria such as being billable in NCPDP format and able to be dispensed by a pharmacy [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Policy Guidelines:12 — 2025-10-01]. The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) requires coverage of home infusion drugs under Medicare Part D [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Policy Guidelines:19 — 2025-10-01].

Regarding billing responsibility, it is the "responsibility of the provider to determine whether the patient is covered by other insurance and whether the insurance carrier covers the service being billed for" [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Billing Guidelines:18, 19 — 2025-07-23]. If the member is covered by insurance other than Medicare, the amount paid by the other insurance carrier must be entered in the "Other Insurance Paid" field [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Billing Guidelines:18, 19 — 2025-07-23].", "similarities": ["Both sources indicate that providers/pharmacies are responsible for determining if a patient has other insurance coverage and billing the appropriate party, including third-party insurers, before Medicaid [New York State Medicaid Update July 2020 Volume 36 Number 12:8 — 2020-07-01], [New York State Medicaid Update June 2019 Volume 35 Number 7:5 — 2019-06-01], [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Billing Guidelines:18, 19 — 2025-07-23].", "Both imply that Medicaid acts as a secondary payer when other insurance is available, requiring other insurance to be billed first [New York State Medicaid Update June 2019 Volume 35 Number 7:5 — 2019-06-01], [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Billing Guidelines:18, 19 — 2025-07-23]."], "differences": ["The Provider Manual explicitly defines how home infusion drugs are covered, stating they are not a bundled payment but must be billed as a pharmacy or medical benefit [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Policy Guidelines:19 — 2025-10-01], whereas the Policy documents do not provide a specific definition for home infusion drug coverage [Insufficient grounded evidence in the provided documents to define this concept for Policy].", "The Provider Manual specifies that home infusion drugs can be covered under both the medical and pharmacy benefits [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Policy Guidelines:12 — 2025-10-01], a detail not present in the provided Policy excerpts.", "The Provider Manual mentions CMS requirements for Medicare Part D coverage of home infusion drugs [New York State Medicaid Program: Pharmacy Manual - Policy Guidelines:19 — 2025-10-01], which is not discussed in the provided Policy documents."], "caveats": null}
